segments.text: The best records that I know of, we have of how we got to where we are, is by writing.
Not necessarily in books, but writing.
And the history of all that has been accomplished, really, is what we have learned by deciphering or reading or studying skeletons, etc., but
Certainly, the written record has been exceptionally important.
I'm interested in the phenomenon of saving writings.
Obviously, I don't have many important writings from the age of a cuneiform.
I just have one tablet, so when my students come, I should show them a clay tablet that was written 3,500 years ago.
I have one piece of Egyptian ... It's an interesting piece of one of their scrolls of papyrus.
It's also very old.
I never thought anybody could read it, including several Egyptian students that I've had.
So that's a little before our time.
And a few manuscripts, one time or another.
Mostly, I guess, all I've got are the books that have been important in the development of medicine.
From that time to this, that I've been able to find and enjoy looking at, studying how they were made and where they've been, if possible.
and learning what it was that they gave to us in the formation of the practice of medicine, if you like.
The science, the art, the problems.
Did you start collecting prior to becoming a physician?
No.
Prior to becoming a physician,
I was a medical student, and once I was a physician, I was doing research.

And there, of course, was involved with reading records of other investigators who had worked in the same field, which is, in part, learning the history of my special function of the intestinal tract.
So that, you know, you start looking at that, and then you develop into looking at other things as well.
I wonder what brought you to the collecting of the book.
Well, that had nothing to do with any reality.
A local book dealer gave a talk to our library association, and he had for sale a copy of The Sages, which was the first modern anatomy book.
That was published in 1542.
But prior to that time, anatomy was really gross.
It was impossible to be useful.
It so happened that he had an artist who obviously studied his dissections with him, and who was able to draw the anatomy of the human being.
that is as good as any modern.

Italian physician who actually had prepared wood blocks.

The illustrations that he made, except a few of the kidney, but the gross anatomy was published in 1714, I think it was.

The other doctor sued him, and the court would not let him publish.
